Got it—here’s the complete end-to-end flow for physical servers, from capturing the image → cloning → auto-provisioning K3s using cloud-init (NoCloud ISO).

I’ll keep it practical and production-oriented.


---

🧱 OVERVIEW (what you’ll achieve)

1. Prepare one golden physical server


2. Capture its disk as an image


3. Clone that image to other servers


4. Attach per-node cloud-init ISO


5. Boot → each server becomes independent K3s single-node




---

🖥️ STEP 1 — Prepare the Golden Physical Server

This is your base machine

1. Install Ubuntu

Minimal or server edition

Ensure:

SSH working

Internet access (for now)




---

2. Install cloud-init

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y cloud-init


---

3. Remove any static network config

⚠️ IMPORTANT — keep image generic

sudo rm -f /etc/netplan/*.yaml

(or leave DHCP if needed)


---

4. DO NOT install K3s here

👉 K3s must be installed via cloud-init later
Otherwise all clones will share same state ❌


---

5. Clean the system (CRITICAL STEP)

sudo cloud-init clean --logs

sudo rm -f /etc/ssh/ssh_host_*
sudo truncate -s 0 /etc/machine-id
sudo rm -f /var/lib/dbus/machine-id

Optional cleanup:

sudo apt clean


---

6. Shutdown

sudo poweroff


---

💾 STEP 2 — Take Image from Physical Server

You have two main methods


---

🔹 Method A — Using dd (simple, raw image)

Boot the server using:

Live Ubuntu USB


Then:

sudo dd if=/dev/sda of=/mnt/usb/ubuntu-golden.img bs=4M status=progress
sync

👉 If NVMe:

sudo dd if=/dev/nvme0n1 of=/mnt/usb/ubuntu-golden.img bs=4M status=progress


---

🔹 Method B — Using Clonezilla (recommended)

Why better:

Faster

Compressed

Reliable for multiple systems


Steps:

1. Boot Clonezilla ISO


2. Choose:

device-image

save to USB/NFS



3. Select disk → save image




---

📦 STEP 3 — Prepare Target Servers

For each new physical server:


---

1. Restore the image

If using dd:

sudo dd if=ubuntu-golden.img of=/dev/sda bs=4M status=progress


---

If using Clonezilla:

Boot Clonezilla

Restore image to disk



---

📄 STEP 4 — Create Cloud-Init Files (Per Node)

Each server gets its own config.


---

📄 user-data (example node-1)

#cloud-config

hostname: k3s-node-1
manage_etc_hosts: true

network:
version: 2
ethernets:
nic0:
match:
name: "e*"
dhcp4: false
addresses:
- 192.168.1.101/24
gateway4: 192.168.1.1
nameservers:
addresses: [8.8.8.8, 1.1.1.1]

ssh_deletekeys: true
ssh_genkeytypes: ['rsa', 'ecdsa', 'ed25519']

bootcmd:

- rm -f /etc/machine-id
- systemd-machine-id-setup

runcmd:

- |
  echo "Waiting for network..."
  until ping -c1 8.8.8.8 >/dev/null 2>&1; do sleep 2; done

- |
  curl -sfL https://get.k3s.io | 
  INSTALL_K3S_EXEC="server 
  --node-ip=192.168.1.101 
  --node-external-ip=192.168.1.101 
  --disable=traefik" 
  K3S_KUBECONFIG_MODE="644" sh -

final_message: "K3s ready"
---

📄 meta-data

instance-id: k3s-node-1
local-hostname: k3s-node-1


---

💿 STEP 5 — Create Seed ISO

sudo apt install -y genisoimage

genisoimage -output seed-node-1.iso \
  -volid cidata \
  -joliet -rock \
  user-data meta-data


---

🔌 STEP 6 — Attach ISO to Physical Server

Use one of:

Option 1 — USB

Write ISO to USB

Plug in


Option 2 — BMC (best)

iLO / iDRAC / IPMI virtual media

Mount ISO remotely



---

🚀 STEP 7 — Boot the Server

On boot:

cloud-init will:

1. Detect ISO (cidata)


2. Apply config


3. Set static IP


4. Regenerate:

machine-id

SSH keys



5. Install K3s


6. Start cluster




---

🔍 STEP 8 — Verify

SSH:

ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.101

Check:

sudo kubectl get nodes
sudo kubectl get pods -A


---

🔁 STEP 9 — Repeat for more servers

Just change:

Item	Example

IP	192.168.1.102
Hostname	k3s-node-2
instance-id	k3s-node-2


👉 Same image, different ISO


---

⚠️ Common mistakes (real-world)

❌ Forgetting to clean image

→ cloud-init won’t run

❌ Installing K3s in golden image

→ duplicated cluster state

❌ Reusing same ISO

→ IP conflict

❌ Wrong disk (sda vs nvme)

→ system won’t boot


